description: From French caraque (compare Spanish and Portuguese carraca, Italian caracca), from Latin carraca, from Latin carrus (“wagon”); or perhaps from Arabic قَرَاقِير‎ (qarāqīr).

entries.meaning: (historical) A large European sailing vessel of the 14th to 17th centuries similar to a caravel but square-rigged on the foremast and mainmast and lateen-rigged on the mizzenmast.
examples: Faith, he tonight hath boarded a land carrack; if it prove lawful prize, he's made for ever.
